(e)

# function to compute RMSE
RMSE <- function(y, y_hat) {
  sqrt(mean( (y - y_hat)^2 ))
}
pred_rf1 <- predict(rf1, newdata = stack_overflow_test)
pred_lm2 <- predict(lm2, newdata = stack_overflow_test)
pred_t1 <- predict(t1, newdata = stack_overflow_test)
RMSE(stack_overflow_test$salary, pred_lm2)
## [1] 23.41256
cor(stack_overflow_test$salary,pred_lm2)^2
## [1] 0.6582163

RMSE for multiple linear regression is 23.56044 and R2 value is 66%.

RMSE(stack_overflow_test$salary, pred_t1)
## [1] 25.06021
cor(stack_overflow_test$salary,pred_t1)^2
## [1] 0.6094537

For regression tree , RMSE is 25.1415 and R2 value is 61%.

RMSE(stack_overflow_test$salary, pred_rf1)
## [1] 23.56502
cor(stack_overflow_test$salary,pred_rf1)^2
## [1] 0.6537861

For random forest model, RMSE is 17.49088 and R2 value is 81%.

For random forest model, we got lower RMSE and higher R2 value than others model. Because of lower RMSE and largest R2 value, random forest is best model than others two.

  ggtitle("Random Forest")

Depend upon the plot of actual vs predicted values,we can say that random forest model is best fit.

For regression tree, predicted values are calculated by averaging the actual value in each region. So the graph looks different like actual values are look like continuous and predicted values are discrete.
